(fifthQuint)Neuromuscular Fatigue Aetiology Comparison Between Prepubertal Boys and Adults.

 The study of neuromuscular fatigue in children is a recently topic in the field of sport sciences.

 Such knowledge could improve the efficiency and security of training and rehabilitation in healthy children and children with diseases like obesity.

 The LENGTH-FATIG study will provide knowledge about the peripheral and central mechanisms of the neuromuscular fatigue in children and adults.

 Fatigue will test for different muscle groups (knee extensors and ankle plantar flexors) at different muscle lengths (short, optimal and long).

 During high-intensity exercise, prepubertal children are more resistant to fatigue than adults.

 Contributions of the central and peripheral components to the development of neuromuscular fatigue are also different between both populations.

