 muscular) fatigue.

 This might be attributed to the fact that prepubertal children rely more on oxidative than anaerobic metabolism than adults during fatiguing exercise.

 On the other hand, nervous factors could also explain differences in fatigue between children and adults.

 However, this topic is scarcely documented and still controversial.

 To our knowledge, no study has still compared the aetiology of central fatigue (supra-spinal vs.

 spinal) between children and adults.

 Only the voluntary activation level had been studied in children, conventionally used to assess central fatigue.

 But this factor doesn't differentiate spinal and supra-spinal contributions to neuromuscular fatigue development.

 The LENGTH-FATIG research project is a physiological and observational study comparing two age groups (adults and children).

 Subjects will have to perform three randomized fatigue protocols at three muscle lengths (short, optimal and long) with the knee extensors and the ankle plantar flexors.

